    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2282058749" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2282058749" />
    <a title="MichelleH H" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/41397839-michelleh-h"><img alt="MichelleH H" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2282058749?book_show_action=true">Feb 02, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="MichelleH H" class="user" itemprop="url" name="MichelleH H" href="/user/show/41397839-michelleh-h">MichelleH H</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41397839-michelleh-h?shelf=audible-version">audible-version</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41397839-michelleh-h?shelf=2021-jaff-tbr-challange">2021-jaff-tbr-challange</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41397839-michelleh-h?shelf=favorite-reread">favorite-reread</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41397839-michelleh-h?shelf=have-audible-version">have-audible-version</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/41397839-michelleh-h?shelf=favorite-audible-listen">favorite-audible-listen</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2282058749" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3810319686597736383">Since I&apos;m trying hard to get better at reviewing (but shamefully will never reach the level of my favorite reviewers here on GR,) I now have to confess that I&apos;ve lost count of how many times I&apos;ve reread or re-listened to this story. I read it the first time when I bought it in 2017. I try to space my rereads apart, though. That ensures I will have forgotten enough details that make the rereading compelling since I cannot remember how it ends. <br/><br/>But oh boy, there are so many deliciously lovely thin</span>
  <span id="freeText3810319686597736383" style="display:none">Since I'm trying hard to get better at reviewing (but shamefully will never reach the level of my favorite reviewers here on GR,) I now have to confess that I've lost count of how many times I've reread or re-listened to this story. I read it the first time when I bought it in 2017. I try to space my rereads apart, though. That ensures I will have forgotten enough details that make the rereading compelling since I cannot remember how it ends. <br /><br />But oh boy, there are so many deliciously lovely things in this story to rediscover. Some of my favorite scenes of any JAFF have been written by KaraLynne, God bless her. <br /><br /><a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ The scene in the maze at Rosings when Darcy discovers Lizzy asleep in the center of the maze near the fountain, one of Darcy's favorite old retreats from his childhood and attached to loving memories of his father. Oh my gosh this was swoony. Elizabeth awakens with a shock when she sees him near by. He rescues her when her bonnet gets tangled in the shrubbery right under a bee's nest. He gets stung, she takes his hand and puts cold water from the fountain on it with her handkerchief. They have some conversation that helps dispel some of the tension following the horrid proposal. She is humbled about her mistake regarding Wickham. Darcy fantasizes about her coming into his arms. They seem to get closer with talking. He offers his handkerchief in exchange of her dirtied one. Then he says something pretty endearing (to us) but alarming and way too fast for Elizabeth, about her kissing his 'wound' to make it better. She flees. But I have a big grin on my face just remembering it. It's one of those...'did I say that out loud?' moments. <br /><br />Another favorite scene and one I wish so many times that other authors would use in some way, is when Lizzy encounters the slimy Wickham in Meryton. He seems to be especially aggressive in his overt flirting with her. Asking how her trip went and meeting Lady Catherine, etc. She turns the tables on him when she spies the local biggest gossip in the same shop she is with her sisters. Lizzy asks him why he hasn't sought another living elsewhere after not getting Pemberley's living. She notes her cousin had no connections before his getting Lady Catherine's preferment. Especially with the education he received because of Mr Darcy Sr.'s benevolence. (Ears are perking up around her as she speaks...) When he states his vocation is now the militia, she says his inheritance must make that possible living off the interest of his 4,000 pounds. (We hear a gasp.) And Wickham tells Lizzy he is needed back at the camp. We learn soon after that he has sold his commission and fled leaving a lot of debt behind and more than several ladies feeling abandoned. I enjoyed Wickham's ironic end in this book. <br /><br />Oh there are so many good ones. Elizabeth receiving a dozen letters from Darcy (heart in my throat, mercifully discovered in the post before anyone else sees it) she was never supposed to have seen. You witness her heart melting like a puddle at her feet. The trip to The Lakes is shortened to just Derbyshire (hurray!!!) Darcy and Elizabeth meet again. He's been working on the rebukes she made with his proposal. When Lizzy and the Gardiners come the next day as requested they are already engaged. Lizzy presented Darcy with his letters the day before. He had no idea they were missing. She looks at him and he sees his letters have changed her mind and proposes on the spot, she accepting. And in this variation Lydia still elopes but actually marries, another officer from Brighton. Oh, there's some angst and tears when her elopement is discovered because now Lizzy thinks Darcy would be shamed by her family's disgrace and she tries to release him. Of course we know Darcy will do anything to keep Elizabeth. More and more sweet scenes.  <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /><br />I happen to like epilogues. This is just me, because I don't understand why others dislike them so much. Unless it's an epilogue that is bad, and this one is not! <br /><br />I love Mackrory's writing. I read 'Haunting Mr. Darcy' at least once a year. <br /><br />I can't recommend this highly enough! <br /><br />I'm so glad that Mackrory's books were taken under the wings of Quills &amp; Quartos reissuing them last year. Her books deserve a look from every new to JAFF reader since her books were originally released. There's such wealth here. It would be so easy for new JAFF readers to read only new works since there are so many. <br /><br />Because this review is also for the audio version, I will also give the narration 5*. Brady Smith's gorgeously deep voice is so wonderful whether he is acting Darcy or Col. F. or even Mr. Bennet. His female characters shine too. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3810319686597736383" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


